title: Grateful Dead Live at Kiel Auditorium on 1982-08-04
description:
Set 1

Feel Like A Stranger, Friend Of The Devil-> CC Rider, Brown Eyed Women, Mama Tried, Mexicali Blues, Row Jimmy-> Looks Like Rain, Stagger Lee, Promised Land

Set 2

Good Time Blues-> Estimated Prophet-> Terrapin Station-> Drums-> Not Fade Away-> Black Peter-> Around & Around-> Good Lovin', E: U.S. Blues

reviews.review_text:
Another good one from Kiel Auditorium! This show is tricky to figure out. For one thing, Phil’s bass is way too quiet. I don’t think it has to do with the SBD recording, since even in the audience tape patches, you can barely hear him. And there’s a lot of those patches. I know we’re privileged just to have any early ‘80s SBDs at all, and AUD patches are just part of the game, but this recording gets split up quite a bit.

On the other hand, this show has some great moments. I really like these blues tunes. Looks Like Rain is great. There’s a fascinating jam out of Terrapin Station and into Drums. They close the show with a bunch of rockers, and spark up U.S. Blues as the rowdy encore. It’s also a treat to hear Brent on his Yamaha electric grand piano. He only had this particular grand piano sound for about a year, and while the man is probably most famous for his fiery vocals and his chops with a Hammond B3 organ, shows like this prove that he was a wonderfully adept pianist as well, and a perfect instrumental foil for Jerry Garcia.

Listening experience aside, based on other reviews on various websites, this seems like it would’ve been a cool one to have attended. The first Dead show for many who were there. Tour kids tripping in the Gateway Arch. What fun!

I haven’t listened to them yet, but the Manor Downs, Zoo Amphitheater, and Alpine shows are better-known, so they could be better shows overall. Just looking at their setlists, they seem awesome. While not as famous, 8/4/82 is good, and it has inspired moments. It’s not consistently saturated with the X factor from start to finish, but the X factor does pop up several times. Overall, it’s a good fun sampler of the sound and approach they were working with in Summer ‘82, which remains a unique and very underrated chapter of the Long Strange Trip.

I left St. Louis, city of blues.
